The '''Dodge Caravan''' (also known as the '''Dodge Grand Caravan''') is a series of minivans produced by [[Chrysler]] since the 1984 model year. Marketed as the [[Dodge]] version of the [[Chrysler minivans]], the Caravan is currently in its fifth generation of production. Introduced alongside the [[Plymouth Voyager]], the Caravan was also sold by Chrysler as the [[Chrysler Town & Country]] until its 2017 replacement by the [[Chrysler Pacifica (minivan)|Chrysler Pacifica]].

Largely marketed in the United States and Canada, the Dodge Caravan was marketed in Europe as the [[Chrysler Voyager]]. From 2009 to 2014, Volkswagen marketed the [[Volkswagen Routan]], a rebadged version of the Dodge Grand Caravan.

Since its November 1983 introduction for the 1984 model year, the Dodge Caravan has been assembled at [[Windsor Assembly]], in [[Windsor, Ontario]], Canada; prior to 2010, [[Saint Louis Assembly]] (in [[Fenton, Missouri]]) was an additional source of production. Since their introduction in late 1983, over 14.6 million Chrysler minivans (including rebadged variants and export versions) have been sold worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motor1.com/news/303790/chrysler-dodge-minivan-35th-anniversary/|title=Chrysler And Dodge Minivans Get 35th Anniversary Editions|last=Gr|first=Chrysler Pacifica Chrysler Pacifica Hybrid Dodge|last2=Caravan|website=Motor1.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>

{{TOC limit|2}}

== Background ==

At the end of 1977, Chrysler commenced development on what would become the [[Chrysler minivans]].<ref name=":1">{{cite web|url= https://www.allpar.com/model/m/history.html|title=Creating the Plymouth, Dodge, and Chrysler Minivan: The Caravan/Voyager Development Story|website=www.allpar.com|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref> Alongside the ability to park within a standard-height garage, designers sought to develop a vehicle with a low floor and car-like [[Noise, vibration, and harshness|NVH]] levels.<ref name=":1" /> While front-wheel drive was sought out for the design, rear-wheel drive was still considered an alternative for cost reasons.<ref name=":1" /> Following the move of both Hal Sperlich and [[Lee Iacocca]] from Ford to Chrysler in late 1978, the Chrysler minivan design (codenamed T-115 at the time) adopted front-wheel drive.<ref name=":1" />

While the Dodge Caravan (and Plymouth Voyager) shared no chassis underpinnings with the [[Chrysler K platform|K-cars]], the two model lines retained mechanical commonality, sharing engines and transmissions.<ref name=":1" />

