The '''Dodge 440''' is a [[full-size car]] that was marketed by Dodge from 1962 to 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/Dodge/1962_Dodge/1962_Dodge_Dart_440_Story_001/1962%20Dodge%20Dart%20440%20Story-01.html |title=1962 Dodge Dart 440 Story (brochure) |page=1 |publisher=Oldcarbrochures.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref> {{clear}}
==Dodge Dart 440 (1962)== [[File:1962 Dodge Dart 440 Convertible.JPG|right|thumb|1962 Dodge Dart 440 convertible]] Introduced in 1962, the Dodge Dart 440 model was the upmarket trim version of the [[Dodge Dart]].<ref name=Gunnell/> Included was the standard equipment of the Dart and Dart 330, plus backup lights and exterior moldings.<ref name=Gunnell>{{cite book|title=Standard Catalog of American Cars 1946-1975 |publisher=Krause Publications |isbn=0-87341-027-0 |editor-last=Gunnell |editor-first=John A. |year=1992}}</ref> The Dart 440 was available as a 4-door sedan, 2-door hardtop, 4-door hardtop, 2-door convertible and 4-door station wagon.<ref name=Gunnell/> The Dart 440 used the {{convert|116|in|mm|0|adj=on}} wheelbase shared with the Dart, Dart 330, and [[Dodge Polara|Polara 500]].<ref name=Gunnell/>
Standard was the {{convert|225|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Chrysler Slant-6 engine|slant-six]] producing {{convert|145|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/Dodge/1962_Dodge/1962_Dodge_Dart_440_Story_001/1962%20Dodge%20Dart%20440%20Story-06.html |title=1962 Dodge Dart 440 Story (brochure) |page=6 |publisher=Oldcarbrochures.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref> Claimed fuel economy in 1962 at a steady 40&nbsp;mph was 24.1 mpg for the slant-6 engine.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/Dodge/1962_Dodge/1962_Dodge_Dart_440_Story_001/1962%20Dodge%20Dart%20440%20Story-02.html |title=1962 Dodge Dart 440 Story (brochure) |page=2 |publisher=Oldcarbrochures.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref> Optional were V8 engines that included the {{convert|318|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} 2-barrel [[Chrysler A engine|Chrysler A]], {{convert|361|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} 2-barrel, {{convert|383|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} 2-barrel and 4 barrel [[Chrysler B engine|Chrysler B]], as well as the {{convert|426|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} 4-barrel and dual 4-barrel [[Chrysler RB engine]]s. Power seats were $96.<ref name="Gunnell"/>
==Dodge 440 (1963-1964)== [[File:Dodge Phoneix (TD2).JPG|thumb|right|[[Australia]]n built [[Dodge TD2 Phoenix]] based on the 1963 Dodge 440]] From 1963 the 440 was separated from the new, smaller Dart range.<ref name=Gunnell/> It now featured a 119-inch wheelbase shared with the [[Dodge 330|330]] and [[Dodge Polara|Polara]] and available as a 2-door sedan, 4-door sedan, 2-door hardtop and 4-door station wagon.<ref name=Gunnell/>
During 1963 and 1964 [[model year]]s, the Dodge 440 was the mid-range model.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=EnYkzsGr450C&q=The+Dodge+440+was+the+intermediate+trim+level+Dodge+and+included+all |page=287 |title=Standard Catalog of American Cars 1946-1975 |publisher=Krause Publications |isbn=0-87341-027-0 |editor-last=Gunnell |editor-first=John A. |year=1992 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref> It featured less chrome and a plainer interior than the top-trimed Polara.
For the 1965 model year, the 440, along with the 330, was replaced by the Polara, with the [[Dodge Custom 880|880]] taking the Polara's place in the lineup on the new C Body with {{convert|121|in|mm|0|adj=on}} wheelbase. The 426 engine was also no longer available in full-size Dodges. However, the name 440 stayed on as a trim level of the [[Dodge Coronet]].<ref name="Gunnell"/>
