====Charger SRT 392====
The SRT 392 Hemi is a 6.4 liter V8 making {{convert|485|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|475|lb·ft|N·m}} of torque.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.autobytel.com/dodge/charger/2015/srt-392-rwd/specifications/ |title=2015 Dodge Charger - SRT 392 RWD Specifications |work=autobytel.com |accessdate=24 January 2015}}</ref> The Charger SRT 392 also comes with 20-inch forged aluminum wheels, 15.4-inch brake rotors out front, and 13.8-inch rear brake rotors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drivesrt.com/2015/charger-srt/|title=2015 Dodge Charger SRT - driveSRT|work=SRT|accessdate=24 January 2015}}</ref>

====Charger R/T Scat Pack====
The Charger R/T Scat Pack essentially takes the place of the former SRT8 Super Bee in the Charger lineup. The powertrain of the SRT 392 is present, as are the front and rear bumpers, but leather upholstery is optional (as opposed to standard), the suspension uses fixed rate Bilstein shocks, the brakes are slightly smaller, and the wheel and tire package is narrower. The Scat pack shares its exterior look with the Charger Hellcat and features a narrow grille, a hood scoop, tinted headlamps and 20-inch forged wheels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/autos/autos-large/2019-dodge-charger-r-t-scat-pack-review/ar-AADRd7L|title=2019 Dodge Charger R/T Scat Pack: Review|date=2019-07-04|first=Perry|last=Stern|publisher=[[MSN]]|accessdate=2019-10-18}}</ref>

===2020===
====Charger Widebody====
For 2020, a "Widebody Package" is newly available for the Charger R/T Scat Pack, but replaces the normal body Charger Hellcat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motor1.com/news/358934/charger-hellcat-non-widebody-discontinued/|title=Dodge Charger Hellcat Non-Widebody Is Dead, Long Live The Widebody|work=[[Motorsport Network#Automotive Businesses|Motor1.com]]|last=Alaniz|first=Anthony|date=9 July 2019|accessdate=9 July 2019}}</ref> The package mirrors that of the Challenger Widebody. When purchased, the Charger gains the following:
* Widebody fender flares
* 20x11 Devils Rim forged aluminum wheels
* 305/35ZR20 Pirelli 3-season performance tires
* 3-mode Bilstein adaptive damping suspension uniquely tuned for competition use
* 6-piston calipers with 15.4 inch vented and slotted rotors in the front (standard on Hellcat models)
* Stiffened anti-roll bars sized 34mm in front and 22mm rear (standard on Hellcat models)
* New electrically assisted steering system<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a28209074/2020-dodge-charger-scat-pack-hellcat-widebody-photos-info/|title=The 2020 Dodge Charger Widebody Looks Meaner and Corners Harder|work=[[Car and Driver]]|last=Stafford|first=Eric|date=27 June 2019|accessdate=9 July 2019}}</ref>
* Features from the Challenger Demon including race cool down (Hellcat only), line lock and launch control/launch assist<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/cars/2020-dodge-charger-srt-hellcat-widebody-and-dodge-charger-scat-pack-widebody/|title=2020 Dodge Charger Widebody adds grip to tame massive Hemi power|work=[[Digital Trends]]|last=Edelstein|first=Stephen|date=28 June 2019|accessdate=9 July 2019}}</ref>

==Police package version==
[[File:2006 Michigan State Police Dodge Charger 1.jpg|thumb|Dodge Charger of the [[Michigan State Police]]]]
In early 2006, [[Chrysler Group LLC|DaimlerChrysler]] released a new [[police car|police version]] of the Charger. It made its debut at the 2005 [[New York International Auto Show]]. Unlike the civilian version, the police version features upgraded heavy-duty brakes, a severe-duty cooling system, police-performance [[Electronic Stability Control|Electronic Stability Program]], police performance-tuned steering, and a gear shifter that is mounted on the steering column instead of in the center console.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fleet.chrysler.com/v7fleet/StaticFiles/files/BuyerGuides/MY13_Charger_Pursuit_Buyer_Guide.pdf |title=MY13 Charger Pursuit Buyer Guide |publisher=Fleet Chrysler |accessdate=May 1, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140324064332/https://www.fleet.chrysler.com/v7fleet/StaticFiles/files/BuyerGuides/MY13_Charger_Pursuit_Buyer_Guide.pdf |archivedate=March 24, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In place of the center console, Dodge has equipped the police edition with an aluminum plate appropriate for mounting radio equipment, computers, and controllers for lights and sirens. The vehicle's electrical system is specifically designed for integration of siren and light controls, and other police vehicle accessories. The Charger is in use with many American, Canadian, and Mexican police organizations.

The {{convert|340|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} Hemi V8 is powerful enough to accelerate the car from 0 to {{convert|60|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}} in 6.0 seconds and to a top speed of {{convert|152|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>Police Vehicle Evaluation Model Year 2013, Michigan State Police Training Division, Nov 2009, p. 30-33</ref> In Michigan State Police testing, the Charger V8 easily outperformed all other pursuit vehicles in acceleration, cornering, and braking (except the [[Dodge Magnum]] and V6 Charger, which stopped slightly faster in some tests) in the first five years since its introduction.<ref>Police Vehicle Evaluation Model Year 2010 (and ibids 2006–2009), Michigan State Police Training Division, Nov 2009 (and related dates for ibids), p. 30-40 for 2010 publication</ref>

The Charger is in use with numerous police agencies in North America as both a marked and an unmarked patrol car. Law enforcement agencies outside of the U.S. have also purchased the Charger, including police services in Canada, Mexico, [[Chile]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oIvRAqAKaQo|title=Dodge Charger Police Interceptor Carabineros de Chile|first=|last=CarsyTuning|date=April 1, 2014|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> the [[Czech Republic]],<ref>{{cite web|url= http://pardubicky.denik.cz/zpravy_region/straznici-v-bohdanci-maji-novou-posilu-dodge.html |title=Strážníci v Bohdanči mají posilu. Dodge Charger - Pardubický deník |publisher=Pardubicky.denik.cz |language=Czech |date=5 December 2011 |accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> and the [[Middle East]], including [[Bahrain]], [[Kuwait]], [[Lebanon]], [[Saudi Arabia]] and the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{cite web |title=US donates 97 vehicles to ISF |publisher=Now Lebanon | url = https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/archive/us_donates_97_vehicles_to_isf_ |accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> Both V6 and V8 models are used by the Police forces, with highway patrols favoring the {{convert|345|cuin|L|1|abbr=on|order=flip}} [[Chrysler Hemi engine|Hemi]] V8 engine and cities more likely to purchase the base police package with the 3.5 L V6 fuel-efficient engine.{{citation needed|reason=need a source confirming that assertion|date=October 2019}} The Charger is also in service with the U.S. federal government and in its military police services.

For 2009, the base Charger police car came with the 3.5 L V6 and a 5-speed [[automatic transmission]]. The rear is slightly updated, moving the "CHARGER" badge to the right, and replacing the left with the badge reading "DODGE." The V8 version uses HEMI V8 engine shared with the Charger Daytona R/T, rated at {{convert|370|hp}} and {{convert|395|lb·ft|N.m|abbr=on}} of torque.

When the Charger was redesigned for the 2011 model year, the police package version was renamed Dodge Charger Pursuit. In mid-2014, All Wheel Drive (with a mandatory 5.7 L Hemi V8) became optional, along with a BR9 brake package. In 2012, the Dodge Charger Pursuit replaced the [[Ford Crown Victoria]] as the #1 police sedan in North America following the latter's discontinuation, with the AWD Ford Explorer Interceptor soon becoming the #1 selling police vehicle. For the 2015 model year, the Dodge Charger Pursuit also received a facelift like its regular version. By 2017, however, the Charger Pursuit and Explorer Interceptor essentially shared the sales award, as sales of the ultra high performance AWD Charger rapidly increased.

==Production==
The Dodge Charger is assembled at the [[Brampton Assembly|Brampton plant]] in [[Brampton, Ontario]], Canada. The Charger shared the [[Chrysler LX platform|LX platform]] with the [[Chrysler 300]], the newer fourth generation [[Dodge Challenger]], and the discontinued [[Dodge Magnum]].

